## D: Professional Skills

### Gear Up
#### (Micro-Aggressions)

* [Workshop URL](https://github.com/turingschool/gear-up/blob/master/microaggressions_group2.md)

A micro-aggression simply isn't a thing. The articles that discussed the topic suggested that the term is used to typically describe an 'offense' that was taken out of context of misconstrued. The checklist that accompanied the articles, I believe, mixed blatant racism with what it called 'micro-aggressions' to conflate the two and make mundane comments seem more powerful than they actually are. If we as human beings take the default position that the person speaking with us does not mean offense by the statements that are similar to those listed in the gear-up, all of society will be better off.

#### (Journey Mapping)

* [Workshop URL](https://github.com/turingschool/gear-up/blob/master/journey-mapping.markdown)

Journey mapping is an effective way to work through a user experience. Asking questions about the paths people have taken to get where they are, and more specifically the problems they encountered along the way is an excellent strategy for coming up with solutions to issues we as developers may be blind to. As developers it is easy to get into a frame of mind that the applications we are building are easy to use and hassle free. It isn't until we actively seek the opinions of those that use them that we can fully understand some of the more nuanced complexities of the UX experience.

#### (Grit)

* [Workshop URL](https://github.com/turingschool/gear-up/blob/master/grit.markdown)

Grit is a characteristic that is displayed through hard work and effort. Grit is developed through failure. It comes from the idea that success is determined not necessarily by talent or skill, but by work. Someone who is gritty doesn't quit in the face of adversity or conflict but rather pushes harder.

